    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-11-29T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-11-29T15:00:00-05:00" n="752"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d752">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/11–2946: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-11-29T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 29, 1946—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1098. Because of economic and financial considerations affecting prospects for
                    repayment, Eximbank not disposed feel opening new <pb facs="1037" n="1027"
                        xml:id="pg_1027"/> credit to China for Hankow-Canton-Kowloon railroad and
                    Yellow River Bridge projects “would be in the best interests of China or of the
                    United States and Export–Import Bank”. This view not expressive formal action by
                    Bank’s directors, but is quoted from letter<note n="78" xml:id="d752fn78"
                        >November 8, not printed.</note> to Clayton from Gaston, Acting Chairman
                    Bank’s Board, in reply to former’s letter Oct. 29<note n="79" xml:id="d752fn79"
                        >Not printed.</note> transmitting with Dept’s agreement General Marshall’s
                    recommendations regarding these projects. Embtel 1548 Sept. 27. Texts both
                    letters being forwarded<note n="80" xml:id="d752fn80">Under cover of memorandum
                        of November 26, not printed.</note> by Army courier to General Marshall. His
                    and Embassy’s comments on economic and financial considerations cited by Bank as
                    well as political considerations involved would be appreciated.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
